title: For Sale:  Webley & Scott Model 1905 Semi-Auto(Blowback) Pistol, 1905 Birmingham Production, .32Acp(7.65mm)
postcontent: Up for sale is a Rare early Webley and Scott .32 Auto Pistol. Designed by factory manager WJ Whiting, the 1905 auto was Webley's first small-bore semi-auto. Featuring a fixed, 3" barrel and 8-round magazine, the 1905 was designed for military and police use, but never adopted by any government agency. Produced for only one year, it was quickly replaced in catalogs by the the 1906-the more recognizable pistol that gained fame as the officially issued sidearm of the three London Police agencies(as well as Scotland Yard). Very rarely seen on the collector's market, this pistol is a unique find for the collector of Webleys, police or British handguns. Condition: Its in a very good with the pistol retaining better than 70% of the original factory finish. Bluing has faded in placed with noticable wear on the high edges from holstering. Carbon spotting and oxidation are evident, with no rust or deep pitting observed. Original hard rubber grips show wear and checkering loss, as well as matching chips on the rear side of both, with the right grip being otherwise fine, and the left grip showing damage and repairs(see pictures). Markings are well-struck, legible and include the Webley "Winged Bullet" logo on the slid

title: For Sale:  Original Springfield M1835/40 musket
postcontent: Original Springfield Model 1835/40 (cap lock conversion). This is a neat example I picked up a few years ago. The Springfield 1835/40 was the last US-issue musket manufactured in flintlock configuration. This example is one of many that was converted to cap lock, and possibly saw use by the Confederates during the Civil War. The gentleman I purchased it from said it was found near the Prairie Grove battle site in Arkansas. This is a rare contract M1835/40, made by L. Pomeroy under license to Springfield (date appears to be 1844). I believe only 7,000 M1835/40 muskets were made by L. Pomeroy, and some were later rifled and given a rear sight, but this one retains it's original front sight and lack of rear sight. It is a .69 caliber smooth bore barrel. There is pitting on all of the exposed metal, but the metal under the wood or any area that was covered seems to be in much better condition, making me think this was probably a barn find. The middle barrel band was missing, so I replaced it with a reproduction M1842 middle band, as the M1835/40 shared many common parts with the M1842. The ramrod trumpet is also pitted, but the stem is in excellent condition, very strong and not fragile, comes out of its slot very easily. The lock internals were mostly missing, and I began replacing them with parts from an M1842 lock, but it is still missing the mainspring (meaning the hammer is loose). The original nipple was removed and lost before I purchased the musket, but the threads are in good shape. The stock is in incredibly good shape, and the inspection cartouches are still clearly visible on the left side of the weapon. The stock is clearly original. Also comes with the correct bayonet, which came with the musket when I got it, and shows equal wear with the exposed metal on the barrel. The inside of the socket is clean and mostly rust free, though. I believe the musket and bayonet have been together since the war. Rough as it is, it's a great original and rare musket for a wall-hanger or conversation piece.  Asking $475 plus shipping, obo. Cross posted.

title: For Sale:  BEAUTIFUL RANDALL Model 14 - 7.5" ATTACK, SULLIVAN SHEATH
postcontent: I'm selling a beautiful RANDALL Model 14 - 7.5" ATTACK with Sawtooth/Sawteeth/Serrated Back Blade. The knife has a FORWARD CURVED Nickel Silver Hilt. 7 1/2" blade of 1/4" stock. Extra heavy 7/8" wide tang runs through the channel handle, which is firmly fastened with epoxy. This knife was designed to meet the demand for an almost indestructible all-purpose knife, though it is especially suited for combat and survival purposes. It comes with a Green Micarta Border Patrol Handle with brass ferrule for a wrist thong, and an early SULLIVAN'S HOLSTER SHOP Sheath with the TAMPA, FL stamping. The sheath is well oiled, heavy leather with SINGLE-STITCHING. The first batch of 100 or so sheaths sent to RANDALL from G.G. (Sullivan's) for acceptance approval contained some double-stitched and some single-stitched sheathes. This was in late 1986. Thereafter, all Sullivan Sheathes were double-stitched. So, obviously, this is one of the first and few SULLIVAN demo sheathes to be used by Randall. Also, for only the first 2 years or so of production, Sullivan used the Silver Snap. This sheath has the silver snap. Prior to 1986 G. G. (Sullivan's) made almost 100% of their sheathes WITHOUT the hone stone pocket. This sheath HAD a hone stone pocket, but it was removed for some reason. You can see the holes in the leather where the hone stone pocket was prior to removal. The brass rivets have some "greening". Overall very little signs of use. A few small scratches on the blade. I am only posting a couple of photos on this listing. IF INTERESTED, MESSAGE (Email) ME and I will send many more photos. Many containing close-ups of the knife and of the sheath.
